Raw data

Data structure

Publicly available testing data are daily aggregated, splitting by Outcome_tests:

# A tibble: 4 x 4
  Date       Number_of_tests Outcome_tests  Week
  <date>               <dbl> <chr>         <int>
1 2020-01-24               0 Positive          4
2 2020-01-24               3 Negative          4
3 2020-01-25               0 Positive          4
4 2020-01-25               4 Negative          4

Example: first case:

# A tibble: 2 x 4
  Date       Number_of_tests Outcome_tests  Week
  <date>               <dbl> <chr>         <int>
1 2020-02-24               1 Positive          9
2 2020-02-24              47 Negative          9

Time adjusted GAM models

Daily data

min_date <- as.numeric(min(positivity$Date))

tests_daily <- positivity %>% 
  # filter(Week > 4) %>% 
  group_by(Date) %>% 
  summarize(Number_of_tests = sum(Number_of_tests)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  arrange(Date) %>% 
  mutate(Day = as.numeric(Date) - min_date + 1)

tests_daily %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Number_of_tests)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1000)


model_time_day_01 <- gam(Number_of_tests ~  s(Day), 
                          data = tests_daily, 
                          family = gaussian(link = "identity"))

summary(model_time_day_01)

Link function: identity 

Formula:
Number_of_tests ~ s(Day)

Parametric coefficients:

Weekly data

tests_weekly <- positivity %>% 
  # filter(Week > 4) %>% 
  group_by(Week) %>% 
  summarize(Number_of_tests = sum(Number_of_tests))

tests_weekly %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Number_of_tests)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 10000)


model_time_week_01 <- gam(Number_of_tests ~  s(Week), 
                          data = tests_weekly, 
                          family = gaussian(link = "identity"))
